{
  "text": "As with the first presentation of MESCC diagnosis, prognosis, probability of neurologic recovery and time to neurologic recovery are highly dependent on pretreatment neurologic status [CITATION_1] . Patients should be considered for surgical decompression AE RT first as salvage rates appear better despite higher complication rates [CITATION_2] . If a patient is not medically and surgically operable, RT AE steroids should be given. The dose and technique of radiation should be chosen to keep the cumulative dose of RT less than BED 120 Gy 2 [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Using this biological threshold, no myelopathy was observed in 24 patients in the series by Maranzano et al. [CITATION_5] and 124 patients in the series by Nieder et al. [CITATION_6] . Newer RT techniques such as spine radiosurgery and stereotactic body RT can be used to minimize cord dose while dose escalating the tumour, and recent guidelines have been published for re-irradiation cord tolerance specific to re-treatment spine radiosurgery [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
